Case Study: UPI Online Payment Fraud (Fictional Scenario)**

Rohit, a second-year college student, wanted to sell his old headphones online. He listed them on a marketplace and soon received a message from a buyer who seemed genuine. The buyer agreed to the price and said he would make the payment via UPI.

The fraud began step-by-step when the buyer sent Rohit a QR code and instructed him to scan it to “receive” the payment. Rohit, unaware of how UPI works, scanned the code. Next, he received a payment request and was told to enter his UPI PIN to complete the transaction. Trusting the buyer, Rohit entered his PIN. Instead of receiving money, ₹5,000 was deducted from his account. The fraudster quickly blocked Rohit and disappeared.

In this type of crime, scammers exploit a lack of awareness about digital payments. They often target students, first-time users of UPI apps, and elderly individuals who may not fully understand how payment requests and QR codes function.

The consequences can be serious, including financial loss, emotional stress, and reduced trust in online transactions. In some cases, victims may hesitate to use digital payment systems again.

This situation could have been avoided if Rohit knew that receiving money does not require entering a UPI PIN. Awareness, caution, and verifying transactions are essential to prevent such frauds.


